At no applied field, Figure \[fig:nvt\_dens\_dist\_0mV\] there exists a pure toluene core of thickness, which is surrounded by two interfacial layers formed by mixing toluene and water interfacial layers. In the toluene interfacial layer, the concentration of toluene molecules decreases in the direction from the pure toluene core towards the bulk water phases, eventually reaching zero concentration. Respectively, in the aqueous interfacial layer, the concentration of water molecules decreases towards the toluene core. Toluenewater mixed layer is thick, which is estimated as the distance where the toluene density in -direction drops from to from the plateau height . The bulk aqueous phases contain and ions. The density profiles show that ions penetrate the mixed interfacial layers that border the toluene core. Thicknesses of the film core and the interfacial layer are shown in the Table \[table:nvt\_film\_thickness\].
The Figure \[fig:nvt\_dens\_dist\_60mV\] shows that application of field leads to build-up of accumulated positive charges on one side of the toluene film and negative charges on the other side. The peaks of accumulated charges are situated at the boundary between bulk water and interfacial aqueous layer. In the direction towards toluene core, the concentration of ions decreases and reaches zero at the toluene core. Ions penetrate only the mixed interfacial region, which is due to the formation of hydration shells. The Figure \[fig:nvt\_dens\_dist\_100mV\] reveals that field increase up to is followed by accumulation of more charges, bringing enough attractive force that leads to thinning of the pure toluene core by down to , while the thickness of the interfacial layers of toluene and water increases by . A possible hypothesis is that the increased electrical compression reshapes the film topography making it a high amplitude rugged surface and the interfacial layer becomes thicker. The Figure \[fig:nvt\_dens\_dist\_120mV\] depicts the film structure (profile) at and data are averaged over the time interval of . This is the moment () just before the rupturing process takes place.
